<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8367FCE3FD6EFAC2FCF5" blockId="15.[826,1441,687,801]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3FD6EFC5EFD11" box="[826,945,688,709]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The species differs morphologically from its closest relative, 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FBFFFD11FB74FD30" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1062,1179,719,740]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FBFFFD11FB74FD30" box="[1062,1179,719,740]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the presence of a very large dorsal penial fold, very small ventral fold and a ventrally displaced ejaculatory duct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8367FCE3FC96FAD2FC6E" blockId="15.[826,1441,840,954]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3FC96FB8FFC89" box="[826,1120,840,861]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Ecology and distribution:</emphasis>
The species is known only from two sites in the same river. One site is close to the opening of this river into the sea, while the 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FAA9FC58FA4EFC4F" box="[1392,1441,902,923]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">type</typeStatus>
locality is located slightly farther upstream.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8367FCE3FC3CFA9BFA35" blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3FC3CFBBCFC22" box="[826,1107,993,1015]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Comparative discussion:</emphasis>
The taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FA5EFC3CFBBFFBC2" authority="(Schmidt, 1861)" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FA5EFC3CFC67FBC2" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FC44FBDEFBA7FBC2" author="Schmidt O" box="[925,1096,1024,1046]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref17822" refString="Schmidt O. 1861. Untersuchungen uber Turbellarien von Corfu und Cephalonia, nebst Nachtragen zu fruheren Arbeiten. Zeitschrift fur wissenschaftliche Zoologie 11: 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1861">Schmidt, 1861</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Corfu as a valid and separate species was clarified by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FB02FBC1FA72FBE1" author="De Vries EJ" box="[1243,1437,1054,1077]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
. Prior to her study, the 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FBB3FBE0FB29FB87" box="[1130,1222,1086,1107]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FBB3FBE0FB29FB87" box="[1130,1222,1086,1107]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Dugesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations from Corfu were usually considered to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FCE3FBA5FC08FB5B" baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[826,999,1146,1168]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3FBA5FC08FB5B" box="[826,999,1146,1168]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, following a conclusion reached by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FCE3FB47FC1BFB7B" author="Komarek J" box="[826,1012,1177,1199]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="322 - 328" refId="ref17045" refString="Komarek J. 1925. Die O. Schmidt'schen Susswassertricladen von Corfu und Cephalonia, gesammelt von Prof. Wilhelmi. Zoologischer Anzeiger 63: 322 - 328." type="journal article" year="1925">Komárek (1925)</bibRefCitation>
. To avoid future taxonomic confusion, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FCE3FB66FC16FB1A" author="De Vries EJ" box="[826,1017,1207,1230]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
fortunately designated a series of 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FCE3FB09FC71FB38" box="[826,926,1239,1260]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotypes</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FC03FB09FBA6FB38" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[986,1097,1239,1260]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FC03FB09FBA6FB38" box="[986,1097,1239,1260]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (ITZN, 1985; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FA82FB2BFC9EFAFD" author="ICZN &amp; International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" refId="ref16928" refString="ICZN, International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature. 1999. International code of zoological nomenclature, 4 th edn. London: The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature." type="book" year="1999">ICZN, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) restricts designation of a 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FB61FACAFAFEFAFD" box="[1208,1297,1300,1321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
to only 
<specimenCount id="9D740DBBE20D8367FAA0FACAFC4BFA9C" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
that forms the new name-bearing type of a nominal species and thus does not allow it to be a 
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3FAAEFC96FA51" box="[826,889,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">series</emphasis>
of animals, the 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FBE3FAB1FB7CFA50" box="[1082,1171,1391,1412]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
specimens specified by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FCE3FA50FBD1FA70" author="De Vries EJ" box="[826,1086,1422,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984: 104)</bibRefCitation>
represent a morphologically homogeneous set of animals. As 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FB6FFA73FAE0FA16" box="[1206,1295,1453,1474]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
locality was chosen Messonghi River, just west of Messonghi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8367FC8AFA37FBDBF920" blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
The Ermones population was first mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FCE3F9D6FC2AF9CA" author="Ball IR" box="[826,965,1544,1566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="187 - 190" refId="ref15818" refString="Ball IR. 1979. The karyotypes of two Dugesia species from Corfu, Greece (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria). Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 48: 187 - 190." type="journal article" year="1979">Ball (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, who attributed it to 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FB34F9D7FA75F9C9" baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[1261,1434,1544,1566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FB34F9D7FA75F9C9" box="[1261,1434,1544,1566]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same paper the karyotype of presumed 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FCE3F998FC08F98E" baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[826,999,1605,1627]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FCE3F998FC08F98E" box="[826,999,1605,1627]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Corfu was analysed but it is not clear which population was studied, either the one from Ermones or the animals from Messonghi River. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E20D8367FC69F97FFB86F963" author="De Vries EJ" box="[944,1129,1697,1719]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
writes that animals from the 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E20D8367FCABF91EFC24F901" box="[882,971,1728,1749]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FBB3F91EFB36F901" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1130,1241,1728,1749]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FBB3F91EFB36F901" box="[1130,1241,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, i.e. Messonghi River, were analysed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8378FC8AF923FEC7FE05" blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" lastBlockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="539" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
Our integrative analysis of the populations that we sampled from Corfu revealed an unexpected and interesting situation. Molecular analysis of both COI and ITS-1 grouped the various populations sampled into three clades (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E2128378FE48FF18FDBBFF08" author="Sola E &amp; Sluys R &amp; Gritzalis K &amp; Riutort M" box="[401,596,198,220]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" pagination="877 - 888" refId="ref18036" refString="Sola E, Sluys R, Gritzalis K, Riutort M. 2013. Fluvial basin history in the northeastern Mediterranean Region underlies dispersal and speciation patterns in the genus Dugesia (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Dugesiidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 66: 877 - 888." type="journal article" year="2013">
Solà 
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FE17FF18FE10FF0F" box="[462,511,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">et al</emphasis>
., 2013
</bibRefCitation>
). These three clades are also identified as separate entities in the GMYC analysis (
<figureCitation id="1349DAB7E2128378FE8BFEDDFE7AFECC" box="[338,405,259,281]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, entities 1, 2 and 3). One clade was formed by populations 27, 28, 29 and 30 (i.e. north of the San Salvador mountain range). The second clade consisted of populations 33 and 34. The third clade consisted of two samples from basically the same locality, namely Ermones (localities 31 and 32) (
<figureCitation id="1349DAB7E2128378FF1CFE65FEF4FE05" box="[197,283,443,465]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. S2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0D96BAE20D8367FF7DF8FEFE89F8BA" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5297137" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5297137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5297137/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" startId="15.[164,243,1824,1843]" targetBox="[166,775,1338,1794]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E20D8367FF7DF8FEFE89F8BA" blockId="15.[164,779,1824,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FF7DF8FEFEF6F8E7" bold="true" box="[164,281,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Figure 13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E20D8367FEFDF8FEFD46F8E7" authority="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" box="[292,681,1824,1843]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FEFDF8FEFDFAF8E7" bold="true" box="[292,533,1824,1843]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Dugesia parasagitta</emphasis>
Sluys &amp; Solà
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9061A20E20D8367FD6BF8FEFCE4F8E7" bold="true" box="[690,779,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A235A75BE20D8367FD6BF8FEFCE4F8E7" box="[690,779,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Photomicrograph of large dorsal penial fold in specimen ZMA V.Pl. 7118.1.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E2128378FF71FE07FED1FBE0" blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
On the basis of morphological analysis of the populations from Corfu we were able to differentiate between only 
<specimenCount id="9D740DBBE2128378FEEBFDC9FE49FDF8" box="[306,422,535,556]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
. The majority of the populations sampled conformed to the classical diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E2128378FF49FD8AFF11FDBD" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[144,254,596,617]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FF49FD8AFF11FDBD" box="[144,254,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, notably in the presence of a well-developed dorsal fold and a very small or absent ventral fold, and with a central ejaculatory duct. This also holds true for populations that we have not re-collected, but of which material is present in the collections of the NBC: Messonghi River, Marbella beach (now called Par. Ag. Ioannis Peristeron) and Mesaria. However, the population from Ermones (ZMA V.Pl. 7118 + V.Pl. 7119) is characterized by a very large dorsal penial fold, very small ventral fold and a ventrally displaced ejaculatory duct (
<figureCitation id="1349DAB7E2128378FE85FC5BFE43FC48" box="[348,428,901,924]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="15.[164,243,1824,1843]" captionTargetBox="[166,775,1338,1794]" captionTargetId="figure-688@15.[166,776,1338,1794]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 13. Dugesia parasagitta Sluys &amp; Solà sp. nov. Photomicrograph of large dorsal penial fold in specimen ZMA V.Pl. 7118.1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5297137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5297137/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Thus, coincidence of molecular and morphological results suggests that at least the population from Ermones is well differentiated from other populations on Corfu. Therefore, we do here describe this population as the new species 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E2128378FF49FBC1FED9FBE0" authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" box="[144,310,1055,1076]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FF49FBC1FED9FBE0" box="[144,310,1055,1076]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. parasagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E2128378FF71FBE3FE9BFA9C" blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
It remains remarkable that the populations that are geographically closest to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E2128378FDD3FB82FD97FBA5" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[522,632,1116,1137]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FDD3FB82FD97FBA5" box="[522,632,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type locality, namely ZMA V.Pl. 7120 from near Vouniatades (locality 33) and ZMA V.Pl. 7121 from near Benitses (34) (entity 2, 
<figureCitation id="1349DAB7E2128378FEEBFB69FE9AFB1A" box="[306,373,1207,1230]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), differ molecularly so much from the populations in the northern part of the island (entity 1, 
<figureCitation id="1349DAB7E2128378FEC4FB2BFEB0FADF" box="[285,351,1269,1291]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), whereas morphologically they cannot be distinguished from each other, nor from the 
<typeStatus id="54C97890E2128378FF49FAECFF06FA93" box="[144,233,1330,1351]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">neotype</typeStatus>
population.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDC632E2128378FF71FA8EFF1DF8BB" blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
After the separation and description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E2128378FD41FA8FFF31FA51" authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FD41FA8FFF31FA51" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. parasagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the nominal species 
<taxonomicName id="4C72BDB1E2128378FE03FAAEFDA6FA51" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[474,585,1392,1413]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FE03FAAEFDA6FA51" box="[474,585,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
actually forms a paraphyletic taxon, according to all molecular analyses done so far (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3BBC3E2128378FE60FA72FD97FA15" author="Sola E &amp; Sluys R &amp; Gritzalis K &amp; Riutort M" box="[441,632,1452,1474]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" pagination="877 - 888" refId="ref18036" refString="Sola E, Sluys R, Gritzalis K, Riutort M. 2013. Fluvial basin history in the northeastern Mediterranean Region underlies dispersal and speciation patterns in the genus Dugesia (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Dugesiidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 66: 877 - 888." type="journal article" year="2013">
Solà 
<emphasis id="B9061A20E2128378FE2FFA73FDC9FA15" box="[502,550,1452,1474]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">et al</emphasis>
., 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; COI gene tree, 
